'''Pauline Mary Philip''', [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], has been the Chief Executive of [[Luton and Dunstable University Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]] since 2010. She has previously worked for the [[World Health Organization]]. She was made an [[Honorary Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE) in the [[2017 Special Honours]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/620914/2017_Honorary_awards_V1.pdf|format=PDF|title=The Queen has been graciously pleased to approve the following honorary British awards in 2017|website=Gov.uk|accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref>
Philip was appointed the national urgent and emergency care lead by [[NHS England]] in 2016. In 2016 the ''[[Health Service Journal]]'' named her as the fifth most influential Chief Executive in the English National Health Service. <ref>{{cite news|title=HSJ Top Chief Executives 2016|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/topics/workforce/hsj-top-chief-executives-2016/7002753.article|accessdate=17 April 2016|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=2 March 2016}}</ref>
She provides national leadership to ensure the delivery of the urgent and emergency care review and associated elements of the [[Five Year Forward View]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Former nurse named as NHS England urgent and emergency care lead|url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/clinical-archive/accident-and-emergency/ex-nurse-named-englands-urgent-and-emergency-care-lead/7000852.article|accessdate=22 July 2017|publisher=Nursing Times|date=4 December 2015}}</ref>
